<summary>
The webpage analyzes the calendar effect and trading patterns of the A-share market around China's annual Two Sessions meetings. It notes that historically, the market shows a general upward trend with a pattern of 'rise-consolidation-second rise' around the meetings. Performance-wise, indices like the CSI 1000 and ChiNext Index exhibit greater elasticity after the meetings. Market style tends to favor small-caps over large-caps before the meetings, with consumption sectors under pressure but showing stronger elasticity afterward. Sector-wise, technology and growth sectors like computers and communications often lead before the meetings, while consumer sectors like social services and beauty care gain momentum afterward. The analysis also highlights trading clues linked to the 'Five-Year Plans,' illustrating how market themes in the first year of recent plans (2011, 2016, 2021) aligned with key industrial focuses such as domestic demand, supply-side reform, and green development.
</summary>

